<header class="header">
  <h1>Why Frost Dates Matter More Than Planting Calendars</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Climate boundaries outperform fixed dates.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    Planting calendars offer generic dates.  
    Frost dates define your actual climate boundary at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    In a typical year, crop success is constrained not by what a calendar suggests,
    but by when frost historically arrives — and how much heat accumulates before it returns.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Problem With Planting Calendars</h2>

  <p>
    Traditional planting calendars assign fixed dates:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>“Plant tomatoes after May 15.”</li>
    <li>“Direct sow beans in early June.”</li>
    <li>“Start peppers indoors in March.”</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These recommendations are generalized by region.
    They assume average conditions across wide geographic areas.
  </p>

  <p>
    But climate is not uniform.
    Elevation, latitude, proximity to water, and local microclimates shift frost timing significantly.
  </p>

  <p>
    A fixed calendar date cannot account for those variations.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frost Dates Define Your Climate Boundary</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are based on 1991–2020 climate normals
    and framed at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    That means your listed last and first frost dates represent
    the midpoint of historical outcomes.
    In roughly half of years, frost will arrive earlier or later.
  </p>

  <p>
    Frost is defined at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> —
    the temperature at which ice crystals form and many tender crops experience damage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Unlike calendar advice, frost dates are location-specific climate boundaries.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can identify your frost window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Identical Calendars Produce Different Outcomes</h2>

  <p>
    Consider two gardeners following the same planting calendar:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Both transplant tomatoes on May 20.</li>
    <li>Both expect harvest in 90–100 days.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    But Gardener A’s location accumulates 2,200 Growing Degree Days before first frost.
    Gardener B’s location accumulates only 1,600.
  </p>

  <p>
    The calendar date was identical.
    The seasonal heat budget was not.
  </p>

  <p>
    As explained in
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>,
    crop maturity depends on accumulated heat, not calendar time alone.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frost Dates Establish Season Length</h2>

  <p>
    The period between your last spring frost and first fall frost
    defines your frost-free window.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short climates, this window may be 90–110 days.
    In longer climates, it may exceed 160 days.
  </p>

  <p>
    But even frost-free days do not tell the full story.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two regions with 120 frost-free days may accumulate very different total heat.
    That difference determines which crops are viable.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Growing Degree Days: The Missing Layer</h2>

  <p>
    Most warm-season crops develop based on accumulated heat above 50°F (10°C).
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    Each day contributes heat units when temperatures exceed the base threshold.
    Those units accumulate into your seasonal heat budget.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate your available heat using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Planting calendars rarely account for this.
    Frost dates combined with GDD modeling do.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Margin Near the Frost Boundary</h2>

  <p>
    Because frost dates use probability framing,
    planting near the boundary increases risk.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comfortable Margin:</strong> Crop heat requirement is well below seasonal GDD.</li>
    <li><strong>Borderline Margin:</strong> Requirement closely matches seasonal GDD.</li>
    <li><strong>Unlikely Margin:</strong> Seasonal GDD typically falls short.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Planting calendars rarely express risk margin.
    Frost-based modeling makes it explicit.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When Calendars Work — And When They Fail</h2>

  <p>
    In long, warm seasons with abundant heat,
    fixed planting dates may appear reliable because the heat budget comfortably exceeds crop requirements.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short or cool climates,
    calendar-based planting becomes fragile.
  </p>

  <p>
    A crop labeled “90 days” may technically fit within a 100-day frost-free window,
    yet fail to mature if seasonal GDD accumulation is insufficient.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why short-season planning requires heat modeling —
    not fixed-date guidance.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Climate-Based Planning Model</h2>

  <p>
    Reliable planning follows a structured sequence:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Frost Boundary (32°F) → Season Length → Growing Degree Days → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    Step 1: Identify frost boundaries at the 50% probability level.<br>
    Step 2: Define your frost-free window.<br>
    Step 3: Estimate seasonal heat accumulation.<br>
    Step 4: Compare crop heat requirements.<br>
    Step 5: Evaluate your margin before frost returns.
  </p>

  <p>
    Planting calendars skip most of this sequence.
    Frost-based modeling completes it.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Planting calendars use generalized fixed dates.</li>
    <li>Frost dates define location-specific climate boundaries at 32°F.</li>
    <li>Frost timing uses 50% probability climate normals.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days measure seasonal heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Crop success depends on heat budget and risk margin — not calendar labels.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In climate-based planning, frost dates anchor the system.
    Calendars are secondary.
  </p>
</section>